Creating Shot Charts

Today’s main focus is going to be on creating cool visualizations, both because it’s fun and because it can teach us a lot about basketball. Specifically we’re going to focus on shot charts.

The first thing we need is shot data, including information on the location of each shot.

Lab Activity 1: First let’s take a moment to talk about how might we encode the location of a shot on a basketball court in a way that a computer could understand and that could be entered into a database?







Getting Shot Data

OK, now we need to get this data - let’s say for all shots from the 2022-23 season. Luckily the NBA actually has this data publicly accessible through an Application Programming Interface (API).

What is an API? It’s a way for computers to talk to each other, basically. The most common use you’ll have for it as a sports analyst is to use your computer to request data from another computer - in this specific case, from the NBA’s database servers.

Working directly with the NBA’s API can be quite difficult. Fortunately, Saiem Gilani has written the hoopR (get it???) package with a bunch of useful functions to help us out. (The hoopR package also works with men’s college basketball data. The package ncaahoopR also works for men’s college basketball data. The package wehoop accesses data for the women’s college and WNBA games.)

OK, here’s the code we’d use to get this data for the 2022-23 season. DON’T USE IT. We don’t want to flood the NBA Stats API with a bunch of requests for >200,000 shots. I’m just including it so you know what it looks like.

shots22 <- nba_shotchartdetail(
  context_measure = "FGA",
  date_from = "",
  date_to = "",
  game_id = "",
  game_segment = "",
  last_n_games = 0,
  league_id = "00",
  location = "",
  month = 0,
  opponent_team_id = 0,
  outcome = "",
  period = 0,
  player_id = "0", # This is "0" to indicate we want all players. You'd use a specific player's ID (more in a moment) here to get the data just for them
  player_position = "",
  rookie_year = "",
  season = "2022-23", # We want the 2022-23 season
  season_segment = "",
  season_type = "Regular Season", # Want regular season, not playoffs
  team_id = 0,
  vs_conference = "",
  vs_division = ""
)[[1]]

Lab Activity 2: Can you intuit how you might change the code above to get, say, shot data for all players for just the last 30 days (if you were doing this mid-season)?

Note the [[1]] on the last line. This probably looks impenetrable to you. I don’t want to get into what it means right now except to say it changes the data from a list (a flexible type of data structure in R) to the more familiar rectangular data frame.

Do You Have a Moment to Talk About Working Directories?

To import data from a file, we first need to know how R looks for files.

Whenever you open RStudio it sets a working directory, which is the place where it’s going to look for (or in the case of exporting, try to write) any files by default, unless you specify otherwise.

You can see where it is using the getwd() command. Try it in your own script.

#Find out what your working directory is
getwd()

I typically want my working directory to be either:

  1. The folder where the script I’m working in is located, OR

  2. If it’s part of an R Project the parent directory for the project itself (we haven’t learned about these yet, please don’t worry about them).

But what if you use getwd() and notice R/RStudio has chosen a different working directory for some reason?

There are two ways to set the working directory to be the location of the file you’re working in. I usually like to include this code in the top of my scripts, which will ensure the working directory gets set to the script location every time the script runs:

#Set the working directory to be the location of the script 
#or R Markdown document you're working in
setwd(dirname(rstudioapi::getActiveDocumentContext()$path))

Alternatively, more recent versions of RStudio allow you to do this manually by going to the top menu and clicking Session > Set Working Directory... > To Source File Location.

For .Rmd documents, when you knit it the working directory will be automatically set to the file’s location unless you override that somehow. But as you’re working within the script note your working directory may be different and still need to be changed using one of the methods above.

Lab Activity 4: Set your working directory to be the location of this script.

Once we set a working directory we can tell R to search for a file in that directory very easily with the code below.

shots22 <- read.csv("./shots_2223.csv")

The . means “look in the working directory.” I coul have also fed a full file path (for example, "C:/Users/zbinney/OneDrive - Emory University/Statistics in Sports/R_Labs_and_Homeworks/shots_2223.csv"), but isn’t our code much cleaner? It will also work more easily on multiple machines, whereas the full file path will only work on my laptop.

shots22 <- shots22 %>% 
  
  #Change shot units to feet
  mutate(LOC_X = LOC_X/10,
         LOC_Y = LOC_Y/10) %>%
  
  # Calculate more precise shot distance
  mutate(SHOT_DISTANCE = sqrt(LOC_X^2 + LOC_Y^2))

Interlude: Data Cleaning

An unsexy but very necessary part of sports analytis is data cleaning. A lot of data, when you get it, is full of errors and other weird issues - mis-formatted variables, typos, implausible data values, and other incorrect or otherwise un-analyzable data.

Many data analysts report spending 60-80% of their time just preparing data for analysis, not doing actual analyses. This is consistent with my experience. But to try and just get you interested in the field we’re skipping over a lot of this stuff and working with pre-cleaned data because people find cleaning “boring.”

Still, I want to give you at least a little experience with the type of cleaning you’ll have to do in the real world. The NBA API involves a lot of data quality checks and processes to clean the data before sending it out, so this is one of the better datasets you’ll ever get. But even then you always want to check for issues.

A good place to start is by running a simple summary() on the data frame and looking for anything implausible or downright impossible:

Let’s now check for implausible records of shots. In the NBA, the distance the 3-pt line is from the hoop ranges from 22 feet in the corners to 23.75 feet at the top of the arc. Armed with this knowledge, are there any implausible shots in our data?

First let’s check the top and bottom few shot distances for 2-pt shots:

Lab Activity 7: Do you see any shots that worry you? Or any data that needs to be cleaned?

If we identified something that needed to be addressed, we’d have two basic options:

  1. Delete the offending observations entirely using filter(). This is probably fine if it’s a small number of shots, but you never want to throw out data - and especially a meaningfully large proportion of your data - if you can avoid it. Here’s some example code, though:
shots22_clean <- shots22 %>% 
  filter(SHOT_DIST>=21 | SHOT_TYPE == "2PT Field Goal") # Filter OUT shots that don't meet EITHER criterion (21 feet or longer OR 2 pts)
  1. Correct the data. This is tricky though because it requires finding - or assuming - some truth. For example, when whether the shot is a 2- or 3-pointer conflicts with the shot distance, which is correct? You could go back and look at game film for every borderline shot, but that would take days. It’s always a balancing act, and looking up case-by-case truths becomes less possible the larger the data you’re working with is.

Plotting Individual Shot Charts

The first thing we can do is create a simple scatterplot of shots, colored by make or miss. But to not overwhelm our computers with 220,000 shots, let’s just do one player: Nikola Jokic of the Denver Nuggets.

#Scatterplot of all shots by Nikola Jokic
shots22 %>% 
  filter(PLAYER_NAME == "Nikola Jokic") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = LOC_X, y = LOC_Y, color = EVENT_TYPE)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(X = "", y = "", title = "Regular Season Shots by Nikola Jokic, 2022-23") +
  theme(legend.title = element_blank()) # Remove the legend title because "EVENT_TYPE" looks bad and isn't necessary

Hopefully this looks kind of familiar already. But it would probably be nicer to have a court overlaid as the background, right? To do this we’re going to use the plot_court() function from Todd Schneider’s ballr (get it? get it???) package. (ballr actually allows you to create interactive shot charts very easily, but I wanted to peel back the layers of the onion a little and show you how to do it yourself.)

Unfortuantely R doesn’t know plot_court() - we have to teach it to R. That’s what the code below is doing. It’s going to look very scary - don’t worry about interpreting it. Just know it’s basically teaching R how to draw a basketball court. That’s it.

court_themes = list(
  light = list(
    court = '#fffcf2',
    lines = '#999999',
    text = '#222222',
    made = '#00bfc4',
    missed = '#f8766d',
    hex_border_size = 0.3,
    hex_border_color = "#cccccc"
  ),
  dark = list(
    court = '#000004',
    lines = '#999999',
    text = '#f0f0f0',
    made = '#00bfc4',
    missed = '#f8766d',
    hex_border_size = 0,
    hex_border_color = "#000000"
  )
)

circle_points = function(center = c(0, 0), radius = 1, npoints = 360) {
  angles = seq(0, 2 * pi, length.out = npoints)
  return(tibble(x = center[1] + radius * cos(angles),
                    y = center[2] + radius * sin(angles)))
}

width = 50
height = 94 / 2
key_height = 19
inner_key_width = 12
outer_key_width = 16
backboard_width = 6
backboard_offset = 4
neck_length = 0.5
hoop_radius = 0.75
hoop_center_y = backboard_offset + neck_length + hoop_radius
three_point_radius = 23.75
three_point_side_radius = 22
three_point_side_height = 14

plot_court = function(court_theme = court_themes$dark, use_short_three = FALSE) {
  if (use_short_three) {
    three_point_radius = 22
    three_point_side_height = 0
  }

  court_points = tibble(
    x = c(width / 2, width / 2, -width / 2, -width / 2, width / 2),
    y = c(height, 0, 0, height, height),
    desc = "perimeter"
  )

  court_points = bind_rows(court_points , tibble(
    x = c(outer_key_width / 2, outer_key_width / 2, -outer_key_width / 2, -outer_key_width / 2),
    y = c(0, key_height, key_height, 0),
    desc = "outer_key"
  ))

  court_points = bind_rows(court_points , tibble(
    x = c(-backboard_width / 2, backboard_width / 2),
    y = c(backboard_offset, backboard_offset),
    desc = "backboard"
  ))

  court_points = bind_rows(court_points , tibble(
    x = c(0, 0), y = c(backboard_offset, backboard_offset + neck_length), desc = "neck"
  ))

  foul_circle = circle_points(center = c(0, key_height), radius = inner_key_width / 2)

  foul_circle_top = filter(foul_circle, y > key_height) %>%
    mutate(desc = "foul_circle_top")

  foul_circle_bottom = filter(foul_circle, y < key_height) %>%
    mutate(
      angle = atan((y - key_height) / x) * 180 / pi,
      angle_group = floor((angle - 5.625) / 11.25),
      desc = paste0("foul_circle_bottom_", angle_group)
    ) %>%
    filter(angle_group %% 2 == 0) %>%
    select(x, y, desc)

  hoop = circle_points(center = c(0, hoop_center_y), radius = hoop_radius) %>%
    mutate(desc = "hoop")

  restricted = circle_points(center = c(0, hoop_center_y), radius = 4) %>%
    filter(y >= hoop_center_y) %>%
    mutate(desc = "restricted")

  three_point_circle = circle_points(center = c(0, hoop_center_y), radius = three_point_radius) %>%
    filter(y >= three_point_side_height, y >= hoop_center_y)

  three_point_line = tibble(
    x = c(three_point_side_radius, three_point_side_radius, three_point_circle$x, -three_point_side_radius, -three_point_side_radius),
    y = c(0, three_point_side_height, three_point_circle$y, three_point_side_height, 0),
    desc = "three_point_line"
  )

  court_points = bind_rows(
    court_points,
    foul_circle_top,
    foul_circle_bottom,
    hoop,
    restricted,
    three_point_line
  )

  court_points <<- court_points

  ggplot() +
    geom_path(
      data = court_points,
      aes(x = x, y = y, group = desc),
      color = court_theme$lines
    ) +
    coord_fixed(ylim = c(0, 35), xlim = c(-25, 25)) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 16) +
    theme(
      text = element_text(color = court_theme$text),
      plot.background = element_rect(fill = court_theme$court, color = court_theme$court),
      panel.background = element_rect(fill = court_theme$court, color = court_theme$court),
      panel.grid = element_blank(),
      panel.border = element_blank(),
      axis.text = element_blank(),
      axis.title = element_blank(),
      axis.ticks = element_blank(),
      legend.background = element_rect(fill = court_theme$court, color = court_theme$court),
      legend.margin = margin(-1, 0, 0, 0, unit = "lines"),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      legend.key = element_blank(),
      legend.text = element_text(size = rel(0.7))
    )
}

Now that we’ve taught R how to plot a court, we can add it to our plot above for Jokic!

Plotting Expected Value of Shots

In the lecture we talked about the expected values of various shots. Let’s investigate that further now.

The coordinates we have are so specific they’ll result in very small sample sizes if we don’t bin them. Specifically, we’ll bin them into areas that are 1 foot in width and height.

# Bin our data before plotting
shots22_bin <- shots22 %>% 
  mutate(LOC_X_feet = round(LOC_X, 0), # Round X and Y locations to the nearest foot to create bins
         LOC_Y_feet = round(LOC_Y + hoop_center_y, 0),
         
         pts = case_when(SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3, # New variable for 2 vs. 3 pt shot to allow for expected value calculations
                         TRUE ~ 2)) %>%
  
  # Create new variables for number of shots and percentage of shots made in each bin
  # as well as whether a bin had >550 shot attempts in a year (roughly, a top-50 location)
  group_by(LOC_X_feet, LOC_Y_feet) %>% 
  summarize(FGA = n(),
            FGpct = mean(SHOT_MADE_FLAG),
            exp_pts = round(mean(SHOT_MADE_FLAG*pts),1),
            FGA_top50 = case_when(FGA >= 550 ~ 1,
                                  TRUE ~ 0)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'LOC_X_feet'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Create base court plot
base_court <- plot_court(court_themes$light)

#Plot expected value and number of shots by bin

base_court + 
  
  geom_point(data = shots22_bin %>% filter(FGA >= 50), # Exclude points with <50 FGA
             aes(x = LOC_X_feet, y = LOC_Y_feet, 
                 color = exp_pts, size = FGA)) + # Color points by expected value, size by FGA
  
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(0.5,4), # Manually set min and max point size 
                        guide = "none") + # Remove size legend
  
  scale_color_viridis_c(option = "A", # Use pretty viridis color scheme rather than default
                        breaks = c(0.4, 0.8, 1.2, 1.6), labels = c(0.4, 0.8, 1.2, 1.6)) + # Manually set color legend labels

  # Specify axis labels, title, subtitle, caption, and color legend label
  labs(X = "", y = "", title = "Expected Shot Value by Location",
  subtitle = "2022-23 Regular Season\n Locations with >= 50 Shots",
  caption = "Size proportional to number of attempts. \n Darker spots are top 50 shot locations.",
  color = "Expected Points") +
  
  theme(legend.title = element_text(size = 10), # Change legend title and text font size
        legend.text = element_text(size = 10), 
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14), # Change title size and center align
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12), # Change subtitle size and center align
        plot.caption = element_text(size = 8)) + # Change caption size
  
  guides(color = guide_colourbar(title.position="top", hjust = 0.5)) # Place color legend label on top of scale and center align

Assessing Player Types

Let’s continue working with our shot data. Let’s begin by summarizing each player’s performance over the course of the season. If a player played on multiple teams we’ll give him a different line for each team since his usage and performance could have changed from team to team:

players22 <- shots22 %>% 
  mutate(pts = case_when(SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3, # New variable for 2 vs. 3 pt shot
                         TRUE ~ 2)) %>% 
  group_by(PLAYER_NAME, TEAM_NAME) %>% 
  summarize(FGA = n(), # Count rows to get FGA
            FGM = sum(SHOT_MADE_FLAG), # Sum um 0/1 SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get FGM
            
            # Do a "Count If" equivalent to get number of 2 pt and 3pt FGA
            FGA_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2])/2,
            FGA_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3])/3,
            
            # Multiply those "count ifs" by SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get number of each type of FGM
            FGM_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==2])/2,
            FGM_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==3])/3) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'PLAYER_NAME'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Mr. Heroball

We’ll define “Heroball” as taking the highest percentage of your team’s shots.

First we need the number of shots each team took. We can get this from another dataset of team box scores available in hoopR:

# Load 2018 team box score data
team_box22 <- load_nba_team_box(2022)


# Calculate shots per team
team_data22 <- team_box22 %>% 

  group_by(team_display_name, team_abbreviation) %>% 
  summarize(FGA_team = sum(field_goals_attempted)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'team_display_name'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.

  1. Wait a minute, there’s something off about that team data. How many rows does it have? How many should it?

Now we have to link this data into the data frame of players we created above. The way we do this is with a join - specifically, a left_join(). I don’t want to get into extreme details, but here’s a great diagram that explains what’s happening.

Basically, we have two data frames with different information: players22 has data on player performance, and team_data22 has data on team minutes and shots. But if we look closely, they share a variable: TEAM_NAME and team_display_name are the same - the name of the team. We can use that to “link” these two data frames like so:

# Join team data to player data
players22_team <- players22 %>% 
  left_join(team_data22, by = c("TEAM_NAME" = "team_display_name"))

Defender of the Faith

What about defense? The NBA play-by-play data actually contains data on who the closest defender is on each shot. One thing we could look at, then, is the shooting percentage on all shots where each player is the closest defender.

# Read in list of players to link to IDs
players <- read.csv("./nba_players.csv") %>% 
  select(PERSON_ID, DISPLAY_FIRST_LAST)

# Code to grab defensive data from NBA API
defense22 <- nba_playerdashptshotdefend(
  date_from = "",
  date_to = "",
  game_segment = "",
  last_n_games = 0,
  league_id = "00",
  location = "",
  month = 0,
  opponent_team_id = 0,
  outcome = "",
  per_mode = "Totals",
  period = 0,
  player_id = "0",
  season = "2022-23",
  season_segment = "",
  season_type = "Regular Season",
  team_id = "0",
  vs_conference = "",
  vs_division = ""
)[[1]] %>% 
  
  # Table from API only has player ID; this code adds in player name from the `players` table above
  mutate(CLOSE_DEF_playerId = as.numeric(CLOSE_DEF_playerId),
         PCT_PLUSMINUS = as.numeric(PCT_PLUSMINUS)) %>% 
  left_join(players, by = c("CLOSE_DEF_playerId" = "PERSON_ID"))

HW Q1: First, read in the shot chart data, save it as shots22, and then modify the code below to add two variables: the percent of shots taken from 3-pt range, and then the mean distance on 2-pt shots. (1 pt)

players22 <- shots22 %>% 
  
  # Change shot location units to feet (rather than tenths of a foot), 
  # and re-create new precise shot distance variable
  mutate(LOC_X = LOC_X/10,
         LOC_Y = LOC_Y/10,
         SHOT_DISTANCE = sqrt(LOC_X^2 + LOC_Y^2)) %>%

  mutate(pts = case_when(SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3, # New variable for 2 vs. 3 pt shot
                         TRUE ~ 2)) %>% 
  group_by(PLAYER_NAME, TEAM_NAME) %>% 
  
  #Create a bunch of new variables
  summarize(FGA = n(), # Count rows to get FGA
            FGM = sum(SHOT_MADE_FLAG), # Sum um 0/1 SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get FGM
            
            # Do a "Count If" equivalent to get number of 2 pt and 3pt FGA
            FGA_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2])/2,
            FGA_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3])/3,
            
            # Multiply those "count ifs" by SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get number of each type of FGM
            FGM_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==2])/2,
            FGM_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==3])/3,
            
            #Add your two new variables here
            ) %>%
  
  ungroup()
